english:
  title: 'Monument Inscription for Lord Yeom of Gokseong: The Loyal Minister of Five Reigns'
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the ninth year of our present reign, in the spring of the Year of the Water Rat, the third month came. The Prime Minister of the Great Peace, the Lord of Gokseong, at the age of seventy-nine, fell into illness. Each day the princes and ministers gathered at his gate to inquire after his health. His halls overflowed with descendants, morning and evening tending to his remedies. Prayers were offered both above and below, leaving nothing undone. The sovereign sent an envoy to ask of his condition, bestowing medicine and wine upon him. Alas! All that mortals can do was done, yet still without effect. Alas! It was Heaven's will.

    The Lord had always enjoyed robust health in his years, and with age his spiritual radiance only brightened. All believed he would live to a great and honored age. Yet this came to pass—can we call it anything but destiny?

    When the Lord's illness came upon him, he instructed his children and grandchildren: "When I pass, let my burial come three days hence. Do not trouble the state with elaborate arrangements." When word of his death reached the sovereign, the ruler grieved deeply. The Prime Minister declared: "Lord Yeom left word that burial should follow three days—we dare not violate his wishes. Yet the state's duty to conduct funeral rites is law itself. To neglect this would be to forfeit our principles. And if we grant no state funeral to such a minister, to whom then would we extend this honor?" Thus they gathered the councils and spared no effort, and nothing was found wanting.

    Alas! In both the Lord's modesty and the minister's action, we see the Way revealed. For ritual is that which makes nations beautiful.

    Let me set down his record. The Lord Yeom bore the family name of Yeom, personal name Jechim, courtesy name Kaesuk, and childhood name Bullo. He came from Seowon, a great family of ancient standing. His remote ancestor, the Venerable Hyeon, served the Confucian Academy in recommending scholars and rose to become Prime Minister. The Venerable Sinryak served under King Myeong, twice conducting the examinations for talent, attaining the rank of Great Master. His great-grandfather, the Venerable Sunyeon, held the rank of Minor Superintendent of the Privy Council when he passed, and was posthumously honored with the titles of Counselor of the Imperial Secretariat and Director of Personnel.

    His grandfather, the Venerable Seungiik, was numbered among the Merit Ministers of the Founding, held the rank of Supreme Harmonizer among the Three Hans, served as Chief Counselor and Commander of the Judicial Oversight, and was given the posthumous name "Loyal and Reverent." He served under King Chungryeol, holding power jointly with Ministers Heo and Jo—names without peer among the worthies of their age.

    His father, the Venerable Sechung, held the rank of Grand Protector of the Forbidden Gate when he passed. His mother was Lady Jo of the Gajun Residence, daughter of Lord Jo Ingyu, himself a Merit Minister of the Founding, ranked Supreme Harmonizer, and Lord of Pyongyang, given the posthumous name "Steadfast and Pure."

    The Lord was born in the tenth month of the Year of Metal Dragon. At six years old, he became fatherless. Raised within the households of both his maternal and paternal families, he was manifestly no ordinary child. At eleven, his uncle-by-marriage, the Chinese Prime Minister Malgi, summoned him to his side and engaged learned scholars to tutor him for ten years. Thus his virtue and capacity came to surpass all of his generation.

    When the great succession was transferred to the imperial seat in the Year of Metal Rat, Minister Malgi led the young Lord to greet the new emperor at Horin. The ruler, seeing him once, marveled greatly. He commanded the Lord to stand constant watch within the imperial palace, showing him favor beyond the ordinary. Though Minister Malgi was a great statesman whom the emperor trusted, his illness prevented his attendance at court. Whenever the emperor had doubts, he would send the Lord to consult at his home, and whatever counsel the minister offered, the Lord faithfully conveyed. When the great official Tieshe was purged and the emperor sought to give the Lord his sister, the Lord replied: "Though I lack understanding, I would not wish to draw near to the company of rebels." The emperor honored him all the more.

    In the Year of the Rat, the Lord besought the emperor: "My mother has not been seen by me for long. Grant me leave to return." The emperor, moved by his words, sent down fragrant offerings to Diamond Mountain, bestowed upon him a golden tablet of passage, thereby lending honor to his journey and hastening his return. In those days, imperial messengers came and went constantly, all wielding the emperor's authority to abuse our ministers and treat our magistrates as though they were beasts. Yet the Lord showed respect to the Prime Minister and courtesy to the magistrates, and made no private petition to the throne. Upon his return, he was appointed Commissioner of the Imperial Wardrobe.

    In the Year of the Snake, further fragrant offerings were sent, and the Lord grew ever more reverent. The elders said: "Though young in years, he brings no shame to those of matured wisdom. Truly he is a worthy descendant of the ministers of both courts."

    In the Year of the Rooster, the Lord, desiring to fulfill his filial duties, sought appointment in the Chengtong Provincial Office. His colleagues there were prone to wielding power for private gain, yet the Lord steadfastly opposed them, restraining much excess. All matters of land and servile disputes he returned to their proper administrators. King Chungsuk marveled, saying: "The Scholar Yeom shows clarity and simplicity." When subordinate officers sought his seal for documents, the king would ask: "Does our Scholar Yeom approve?" If the Lord's seal was there, the matter proceeded; if not, it was halted. That the king called him "our Scholar" showed the affection born of trust.

    The Lord remained in this post for nine years until the king's death. "I cannot remain here long," he declared. Just then he was summoned to serve as Assistant Director of the Directorate of Righteousness, with the rank of Attendant Official.

    In the Year of the Goat, the Lord was sent as envoy to Jiangzhe Province to audit accounts for the Central Planning Bureau. Officials there were quick to offer bribes and seek favor, yet the Lord rejected all such advances. When Minister Bikeabhua rose to power, he treated the Lord with exceptional courtesy. Upon his elevation to the chief ministry, he recommended the Lord to the emperor, saying: "In Jiangzhe, this old minister came to know of Yeom's exceptional integrity." The emperor was about to employ him when the Great Lady fell gravely ill. The Lord earnestly petitioned to return and tend her, and so was not appointed at that time.

    In the sixth month of the Year of the Monkey, the late sovereign said: "Yeom served the Yuan emperor as a court minister and assisted our great-grandfather, King Chungsuk, as a staff official, together plotting for the state. Though he has not yet served in our realm, such service cannot be judged by common measure." Thus was he appointed to the Fifth Rank with oversight of the Right Section of the Three Excellencies.

    That autumn he was elevated to the Fourth Rank. Winter brought promotion to Paramount Counselor. When the Commissioner of the Provincial Office sought to investigate the Record Office officials, directing scrutiny toward the great official Lee Suk, the Lord remonstrated: "The Record Office should not be shaken. Can we so dishonor a man of the age? Should I remain silent, I would betray my learning." He presented the matter to court and it was set aside.

    The Lord rose steadily through the ranks, serving five sovereigns with unwavering loyalty. During troubled times, he showed himself equal to the moment. The three armies obeyed his command, a hundred measures stayed true. He nurtured the people and protected the ancestral shrines, governing with righteousness and rectitude.

    When the Red Bandits threatened the northern reaches, he was appointed Supreme Commander with full authority. The sovereign granted him the symbols of command, saying: "After you depart, I shall not concern myself with the north." The Lord replied: "I too shall not trouble Your Majesty's ear with petty matters." The sovereign, delighted, declared: "Lord Yeom is my ten-thousand-league wall of defense!"

    In managing the army, he made provisions and forage foremost, fortifications second, arms and equipment third. Though he had determined these principles in his heart, he invariably consulted with Vice-Minister Choe, now the Director of Three Excellencies. So keen was the Lord's judgment of men.

    When he at last retired, the scholars all said: "Lord Yeom has held the office of selection five times, yet never has he advanced or dismissed a single person through favoritism or personal grudge. Though his kinship is vast, none of his clan hold positions of prominence. Truly he embodied restraint and freedom from desire."

    Hardy in constitution and bright of spirit, the Lord lived to his seventy-ninth year. Yet in spring of this year, overcome by sudden illness and reflecting upon his long service—twenty-nine years as Minister, five reigns witnessed—he spoke to his sons: "My time draws short. I have lived beyond measure. Let my burial be simple, as I have always taught."

    On the twenty-ninth day of the third month, at dawn, he passed away peacefully in his chambers. Three days later, he was laid to rest in the Great Valley of Rimgang County, as he himself had chosen.

    When the sovereign's envoy Kim Sil came to inquire of his condition, the Lord, properly attired, received the imperial medicine and wine. He then addressed the envoy: "Please convey to the sovereign that this old minister's gratitude is as vast as heaven and earth. I served his predecessors, and now, though my strength fails, my only wish is that he practice caution each day and ensure the realm's eternal stability."

    Alas, the Lord lived without regret.

    The Lord took two wives. His first was Lady Pae of Wansan, daughter of the Marquis of Wansan. She died early, leaving no sons. His second was Lady Gwon, daughter of the Yuan official Han Gong, herself distinguished for diligence and rigor in raising children. She bore him three sons and five daughters, all of whom advanced through talent and virtue.

    His eldest son, Gukbo, became Grand Academician of the Institute of Literary Arts. His second son, Heungbang, rose to Grand Counselor of the Left and Great Master of the National Academy. His third son, Jeongsu, held office as Vice-President of the Secretariat and Supervisor of the Bureau of Rituals.

    His daughters married into distinguished families. One became Royal Concubine Shin, mother of princes. Another wed the Vice-Director of the Secretariat. His grandchildren and great-grandchildren have continued his line with honor.

    Alas! The Lord embodied the five blessings, and his descendants have known fortune. Heaven's generosity toward him must have its reasons—the karmic legacy of generations of loyal service, the bright testament of devotion to sovereign and kindness to all.

    Upon this, the chronicler Saek respectfully offers this inscription:

    In youthful brilliance the Lord ascended the imperial court,
    Returning to lead the provincial chancellery in peace.
    Through five reigns he served with unfailing devotion,
    Raising the nation's splendor, steady as mountains, swift as thunder.

    In those difficult times the Lord proved himself:
    Three armies answered his command with their lives,
    All laws stood firm and true.
    The people flourished, the ancestral shrines stood guarded,
    By his rectitude and integrity, his cultivation and grace.

    The ailments of many were healed,
    The intoxicated were awakened.
    The peace that came was Heaven's listening ear,
    As the virtuous sovereign traced his portrait with honor.

    Rich in merit, resplendent in virtue,
    His image shines eternal in vermillion and gold.
    The elder statesman, model for the nation—
    Why was his span not a full hundred years?

    Heaven and earth grow dim and distant.
    The mountains stand divided from the valleys,
    The streams flow clear and cold.
    There rests the beauty of his sacred ground,
    Where his monument rises toward the stars,
    Unchanging through a thousand ages,
    Illuminating these Eastern lands forever.
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''Five Blessings'' (오복) in Classical Chinese tradition are: longevity, wealth, health, virtue, and a peaceful death.'
    - The 'three days' burial reflects Confucian values of filial piety and simplicity that the Lord practiced throughout his life.
    - The 'ten-thousand-league wall' is an allusion to the Great Wall of China, signifying the Lord's role as protector of the realm.
    - 'Five Sovereigns: Lord Yeom served under Kings Chungsuk, Chunggyeol, Chungryeol, and two Yuan-era rulers, spanning tumultuous transitions of power.'
